<Folder><name>Horn / NE Africa</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇸🇩 Sudan Civil War — SAF vs. RSF ◆</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Sudan Civil War — SAF vs. RSF</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Horn / NE Africa | <b>Index:</b> 98/100 (Δ +1)<br/><b>Status:</b> ACTIVE<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 150,000+ dead; El Fasher 6,000 in 72h<br/><b>Note:</b> HRC passed atrocity-prevention motion Jul 6 (consensus; CHINA disassociated) + urgent inquiry · Türk "red alert... not a drill" · El Obeid besieged from 3 directions, ~500k trapped, ~1 month no electricity · UN documented 15 drone strikes/3wks killing 45+ civilians; UNICEF 330+ children killed/injured H1 2026 · IRONY: UAE (alleged RSF sponsor) pledged $30M "aid" for El Obeid civilians — textbook aid-washing · analyst: El Obeid fall would let RSF reconnect Darfur-Kordofan-central &amp; rebuild political project after losing Khartoum<br/><b>Gov:</b> UN Security Council: Panel of Experts documents arms flows; genocide-determination pressure | US State Dept: Genocide determination (Jan 2025); Boulos envoy shuttle; UNSC briefing | UK FCDO: El Obeid 'on the precipice of an atrocity'; 29-nation coalition | EU Council: Sanctions on 7 individuals incl. Algoney Hamdan Dagalo (Hemedti's brother) | UN OHCHR (Türk): 'Stop this madness' — imminent El Obeid offensive risks serious international crimes; El Fasher playbook warning<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> UAE (Gold + arms channel) [HIGH]<br/><b>◆ External actors:</b> 🇦🇪 UAE→RSF [DENIED]: Weapons, drones, Colombian mercenaries via Chad airlift (109+ flights to Amdjarass); Chinese arms transfer | 🇷🇺 Russia→both→RSF [DOCUMENTED]: Wagner supplied surface-to-air missiles to RSF (US Treasury 2023); now courting SAF for Red Sea naval base | 🇶🇦 Qatar→SAF [ALLEGED]: Discreetly supplied SAF weaponry incl. reportedly 6 Chinese warplanes | 🇪🇬 Egypt→SAF [ALLEGED]: Reportedly provided a drone base for the SAF | 🇹🇷 Turkey→SAF [ALLEGED]: Baykar reportedly funneled $120M+ arms incl. drones/warheads; helped drive RSF from Khartoum | 🇮🇷 Iran→SAF [DOCUMENTED]: Mohajer-6 drones to SAF (2024-25)<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Sudan rises to its highest-ever 98. El Obeid is now besieged from three directions with ~500,000 trapped and no electricity for a month — the El Fasher playbook running in real time. The July 6 HRC 'red alert' motion (passed by consensus, China disassociating) and an urgent inquiry mark unprecedented anticipatory action, but as HRW noted, states still failed to name the UAE explicitly. The starkest data point of the week: the UAE — the RSF's alleged principal sponsor — pledged $30M in humanitarian aid for the very city its client is besieging, the aid-washing dynamic in a single gesture.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>30,15.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Sahel Core</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇧🇫 Burkina Faso — JNIM Insurgency + Military Overreach ◆</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Burkina Faso — JNIM Insurgency + Military Overreach</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Sahel Core | <b>Index:</b> 94/100 (Δ +1)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 50% of all Sahel militant-Islamist deaths; Djibo/Barsalogho massacres<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW STANDALONE · Burkina = highest violence in Sahel (50% of regional militant deaths, Africa Center) · JNIM briefly SEIZED Djibo + Diapaga (May) · ~90 soldiers killed Koubel-Alpha ambush · CRITICAL: Burkinabè troops caused 56% of civilian fatalities Jan23-Mar26 (ACLED) — more than jihadists · IPC Phase 4 famine risk · JNIM displayed photo of Ouagadougou · NEW: JNIM attacked Dargo base (~50 soldiers killed) + pressuring Fada N'Gourma western approaches to isolate it from Ouagadougou · Fada University raid · ACLED: post-defection JNIM campaign = 30+ attacks in Burkina alone, 120+ soldiers/VDP/forest-guards killed; ISSP counter-offensive killed 40+ JNIM (intra-jihadist war)<br/><b>Gov:</b> Burkina Defense/Justice Ministries: Non-responsive to HRW inquiries; dissolved political parties; entrenched military rule via new fundamental law | US State Dept: Senior official Nick Checker visited Ouagadougou (Mar 2026) to 'relaunch relations'<br/><b>◆ External actors:</b> 🇷🇺 Russia (Africa Corps)→junta [DOCUMENTED]: ~100→300 personnel; Loumbila base protecting Traoré; gold-refinery support | 🇦🇪 UAE→state [DOCUMENTED]: Supplied armoured vehicles (documented state-partner side) | 🇮🇷 Iran→junta [ALLEGED]: Ababil-2/Mohajer-6 drone supply agreements (2024)<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Burkina Faso enters as its own theater at 93 — the Sahel's epicenter. The defining dynamic, per ACLED, is the vicious cycle: the army kills more civilians than the jihadists do, which drives recruitment, which the junta answers with more force. The VDP militia that was central to Traoré's mobilization has been gutted. JNIM's seizure of Djibo and Diapaga and its display of Ouagadougou signal a shift from rural insurgency toward urban ambitions — the trajectory to watch.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-1.5,13.0,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇲🇱 Mali — JNIM Economic Warfare + FLA/Azawad ◆</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Mali — JNIM Economic Warfare + FLA/Azawad</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Sahel Core | <b>Index:</b> 92/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 29% of Sahel militant deaths; 207 JNIM deaths Jan-Apr; Defense Min Camara killed<br/><b>Note:</b> JUL 1: JNIM launched SEVEN coordinated attacks across Ségou + Kayes regions incl. Kayes city itself — region home to ~80% of Mali's industrial gold production, previously largely spared · army claims 80+ militants killed; JNIM claims dozens of soldiers + 100+ vehicles + governor's residence damage (DISPUTED figures) · JNIM threatened Kayes/Nioro blockade next day · Crisis Group: testing urban defenses, aiming to "encourage the regime's collapse from within" · 245,000+ Malian refugees now in Mauritania (~5% of its population) · JUL 4: renewed FLA/JNIM offensive at Anefis, Aguelhoc, Gao · Africa Center CONFIRMED: JNIM received $50M from UAE for release of 2 Emirati citizens — direct external-cash-to-jihadist link · JNIM adopting HTS-model (nationalist "single front to dismantle the junta" rhetoric; asked Russia to stay neutral) · army+Wagner mass-grave executions of Fulani continuing (HRW: 22 bodies Diafarabé)<br/><b>Gov:</b> Mali Armed Forces General Staff: Confirmed Apr 25 coordinated attacks 'by unidentified armed terrorist groups'; Foreign Min Diop calls ECOWAS exit 'final' | US/UK Embassies: Urged citizens to 'depart immediately'; pulled diplomatic staff (Oct 2025) | Mali Education Ministry: Ordered schools shut Oct 26-Nov 9 due to blockade | Mali Armed Forces: Claims 80+ militants killed repelling the Jul 1 seven-site assault (figures disputed by JNIM claims) | Mauritania Government: 245,000+ Malian refugees registered — equivalent to ~5% of Mauritania's population<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> JNIM (Commodity + corridor) [HIGH]<br/><b>◆ External actors:</b> 🇷🇺 Russia (Africa Corps)→junta [DOCUMENTED]: ~2,500 personnel; combat ops; gold-refinery support + nuclear/solar deals | 🇹🇷 Turkey→junta [DOCUMENTED]: Bayraktar TB2 drones (displaced French suppliers) | 🇮🇷 Iran→junta [ALLEGED]: Mohajer-6/Shahed drones + IRGC-Quds explosives training; but Quds also coordinates with JNIM for safe havens | 🇺🇸 US (corruption signal)→junta-adjacent [DOCUMENTED]: Trump admin lifted Russia-sanctions on 3 senior Malian officials designated for facilitating Wagner (early 2026)<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Mali rises to 92. The July 1 Kayes strike is a strategic marker: seven simultaneous attacks hundreds of kilometers apart, hitting the region that produces ~80% of Mali's industrial gold and anchors the Senegal trade corridor. Crisis Group reads it as JNIM testing urban defenses and trying to induce regime collapse from within — the urban phase declared in 2024 is now operational. A DISPUTED single-source claim of Ukrainian involvement in coordinating April's attacks (likely info-op) is logged but not credited.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-3.0,17.6,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇳🇪 Niger — ISSP + JNIM + Kidnapping Hub ◆</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Niger — ISSP + JNIM + Kidnapping Hub</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Sahel Core | <b>Index:</b> 88/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 17% of Sahel militant deaths; Kirtachi 12 soldiers killed + 7 captured<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW STANDALONE · ISSP + JNIM outbidding · JNIM overran Kirtachi National Guard camp (12 killed, 7 captured) · ISSP hit Niamey Airport (Jan) + Tahoua Airport (Mar) + Niger-Benin oil pipeline sabotage · record Westerner kidnapping hub · Tiani dissolved parties, 5-yr transition to 2030 · ISSP leader Souleymane Ag Bakawa arrested by Mali/Africa Corps (Ménaka) · ACLED: Tillaberi now DEADLIEST region in central Sahel (1,200+ fatalities 2025, surpassing all Mali/Burkina regions); ISSP primary driver; Tera dept worst-hit (Burkina border)<br/><b>Gov:</b> Niger Government: Confirmed AES Unified Force 'intense air campaigns' after Apr 25; accuses France of sponsoring attacks; cancelled May 1 parades for security | Tiani transitional decree: Dissolved all political parties (Mar 2025); 5-year transitional mandate to 2030<br/><b>◆ External actors:</b> 🇷🇺 Russia (Africa Corps)→junta [DOCUMENTED]: MoU for uranium extraction; security presence | 🇮🇷 Iran→junta [ALLEGED]: Advanced drones-for-uranium deal: ~300 metric tons yellowcake (~$56M) for drones + SAMs + economic aid | 🇹🇷 Turkey→junta [DOCUMENTED]: Turkish Class III armed drones<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Niger enters at 88. It is the ISSP stronghold to Mali/Burkina's JNIM core, and the JNIM-ISSP outbidding competition is driving both toward higher-impact attacks (airports, pipelines, kidnappings). Tiani's extension to 2030 confirms the coup's justification — that juntas would restore security — has not been met. The Nigeria-border bridge is the key expansion vector.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.0,17.6,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Coastal Frontier</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇧🇯🇹🇬 Benin &amp; Togo — JNIM Coastal Expansion</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Benin &amp; Togo — JNIM Coastal Expansion</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Coastal Frontier | <b>Index:</b> 72/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Benin 305 deaths (+76%, record); Togo 54 civ + 8 soldiers<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW · Crisis Group: Benin + Togo 'in greatest peril' · Benin 305 militant deaths = deadliest on record (+76%) · JNIM appointed an EMIR for Benin · Koualou attack (disputed Benin-Burkina border) · Togo: Kpendjal Prefecture worst-hit, 54 civ killed · 450+ incidents/yr within 50km of coastal borders<br/><b>Gov:</b> Togo Government: Established one of the sub-region's most important security systems in the north; Cinkassé/Kpendjal front lines | Benin Government: Military positions at Koualou attacked; disputed border zone with Burkina Faso | AES-ECOWAS (Togo-mediated): Togo FM Dussey offered to 'bridge' AES and ECOWAS — first formal interaction since May 2025<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Benin and Togo enter as a clustered coastal-frontier theater at 72 — the leading edge of JNIM's southward push toward the Gulf of Guinea. Crisis Group names them 'in greatest peril.' The appointment of a Benin emir and the record death tolls mark the transition from spillover to a deliberate coastal campaign. This is the frontier to watch for whether the Sahel war reaches the Atlantic.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>1.5,10.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇬🇭 Ghana — Frontier State + Galamsey Nexus</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Ghana — Frontier State + Galamsey Nexus</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Coastal Frontier | <b>Index:</b> 58/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> No large-scale attack yet; Bawku ethnic conflict deaths<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW · Ghana's own ECOWAS Parliament submission: militants use N. Ghana for LOGISTICAL + MEDICAL support · galamsey (illegal gold mining) named #1 national security threat (KAIPTC) — organized crime/corruption nexus · Bawku Mamprusi-Kusasi conflict · Zongo-community radicalization risk · no confirmed large-scale attack inside Ghana yet<br/><b>Gov:</b> Ghana ECOWAS Parliament submission: Warned militants use N. Ghana for logistical/medical support; risk of escalation within borders | NCCRM (Act 1070, 2021): National Centre for Coordination of Early Warning; monitors crime, governance, terrorism; monthly reports to ECOWAS | NAIMOS anti-galamsey: 3 monitoring bases in Western Region (Ellembelle, Amenfi East, Ahanta West); galamsey ravaged 11 of 14 districts<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> United States (Portfolio securities) [LOW]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Ghana enters at 58 as a frontier state — not yet in open conflict but structurally exposed. The distinctive thread is the fusion you asked to track: galamsey is simultaneously the #1 crime/corruption problem and a potential security on-ramp, linking illegal mining, organized crime, and jihadist recruitment. Ghana's democratic institutions and early-warning architecture (NCCRM) are its resilience; its northern marginalization and galamsey grievances are the vulnerabilities.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-1.0,9.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇨🇮 Côte d'Ivoire — Contained Frontier</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Côte d'Ivoire — Contained Frontier</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Coastal Frontier | <b>Index:</b> 54/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> STALEMATE<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Grand-Bassam 2016 (19 killed); attacks halted 2020-21<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW · Managed to HALT attacks 2020-21 (the coastal success case) · prefect-led refugee vetting + registration model praised by analysts · remains vulnerable to JNIM rear-base use · Burkina-CI tensions (Traoré accuses Abidjan of undermining) · military containment + development combo<br/><b>Gov:</b> Ivorian Government: Local prefects vet incoming refugees + register displaced families to prevent infiltration — model cited by ISS/analysts | Military containment: Northern border force posture; combined with socio-economic development programs<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> United States (Portfolio securities) [LOW]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Côte d'Ivoire enters at 54 as the containment counter-model — proof the coastal advance is not inevitable. Its prefect-vetting approach is cited across the analyst literature as the template Ghana, Benin, and Togo are urged to adopt. The risk is less internal insurgency than becoming collateral to Burkina Faso's instability and JNIM's rear-base needs.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-5.5,8.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Central Africa</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇨🇩 DRC — M23/Rwanda + ADF + Cobalt + Ebola ◆</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>DRC — M23/Rwanda + ADF + Cobalt + Ebola</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Central Africa | <b>Index:</b> 82/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 10,000+ since 2022; ADF killed 149 civ in Ituri last month (ACLED)<br/><b>Note:</b> UPDATED · ADF killed 149 civilians in Ituri last month (=Jan-Apr total combined, ACLED) · Ebola now in 4th province (Bundibugyo strain, WHO) · ADF shifting north from N.Kivu into Ituri = both violence hotspot + Ebola-response center · M23 took Uvira; FARDC killed M23 spokesman Ngoma in record drone campaign · DRC + M23 pledged comprehensive peace agreement by MID-AUGUST; both sides reinforcing South Kivu — possible imminent battle for Uvira · Uvira status murky: M23 claimed retreat under US pressure but plainclothes militants still occupy + clash with Wazalendo · FARDC record air/drone campaign (killed spokesman Ngoma) around Rubaya coltan mine · Rwanda-Burundi powder keg (Uvira 26km from Bujumbura); comprehensive peace deal still pledged mid-Aug<br/><b>Gov:</b> WHO: Confirmed Ebola (Bundibugyo virus) spread to 4th province; Ituri insecurity limiting containment | DRC Government / FARDC: Record drone/air campaign; killed M23 spokesman Willy Ngoma | G7 / Élysée: Critical Minerals Alliance targeting cobalt/rare-earth concentration<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> China / G7 (Critical minerals) [HIGH]<br/><b>◆ External actors:</b> 🇨🇳 China→state/economic [DOCUMENTED]: CMOC mines most DRC cobalt; ships raw metal to China for processing | 🇺🇸 US→economic counter [DOCUMENTED]: EGC/EVelution/Trafigura tripartite MoU (May 2026) to counter China cobalt lead<br/><b>Assessment:</b> DRC rises to 82. The compounding factor is the ADF-Ebola convergence in Ituri: the same territory is the Islamist-violence hotspot and the epidemic epicenter, and the violence is actively preventing the epidemic response — a lethal feedback loop. Rwanda's M23 proxy (now holding Uvira) remains the 'hi' geopolitical lever; the ADF is the humanitarian accelerant.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>29.2,-1.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇳🇬 Nigeria — ISWAP + Ansaru + Bandits + IPOB ◆</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Nigeria — ISWAP + Ansaru + Bandits + IPOB</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Central Africa | <b>Index:</b> 68/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Tumfa airstrike: Amnesty alleges 100+ civilians; Niger/Kwara fatalities doubled<br/><b>Note:</b> UPDATED · JNIM claimed its FIRST Nigeria attacks (killed soldiers, Kwara/Niger border) · Ansaru re-emergence (AQIM/JNIM-allied), shifted to Kwara/Niger States · Lakurawa (ISGS-linked) in Kebbi/Sokoto, cooperating w/ Boko Haram Sadiku faction · ISWAP officer-killings (5 in 5 months) · banditry = most armed violence in NW<br/><b>Gov:</b> Nigerian Armed Forces: Multi-front operations; to embed journalists to improve security reporting; requested French support | US/France: ISR + Lakurawa precision airstrikes; deepening security footprint | CBN / NUPRC: FX reform + petroleum licensing — economic stability layer<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> United States (Portfolio securities) [MED]<br/><b>◆ External actors:</b> 🇹🇷 Turkey→state [DOCUMENTED]: TB2s, Songar tactical drones, ANKA-S co-production talks; tied to Dec strike that killed 85+ civilians | 🇦🇪 UAE→state [DOCUMENTED]: Armoured vehicles used vs Boko Haram | 🇨🇳 China→state [DOCUMENTED]: 72 drones (Wing Loong, CH-series); no human-rights conditionality | 🇮🇷 Iran→soft-power [ALLEGED]: Al-Mustafa University network + cultural centres (Abuja) — ideological screening/recruitment nodes<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Nigeria rises to 68. It is the hinge where the Sahel and Lake Chad theaters are fusing: JNIM's first Nigeria strikes, Ansaru's revival, and the Lakurawa-Boko Haram cooperation all point to a merging jihadi geography across the Niger-Nigeria border. The four-front problem (ISWAP, Sahel-linked groups, bandits, IPOB/ESN) makes Nigeria the most multi-dimensional theater in West Africa.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.5,11.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Caribbean</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇭🇹 Haiti — Viv Ansanm / State Collapse</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Haiti — Viv Ansanm / State Collapse</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Caribbean | <b>Index:</b> 94/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 16,000+ killed since 2022; 2,300 killed in 2026 alone<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW · Viv Ansanm controls ~70-90% of Port-au-Prince · US-designated FTO · no president since Moïse assassination (2021) · UN Gang Suppression Force deploying (&lt;1,000 of planned 5,550; Chad/Kenya) BUT badly underfunded · Defense Ministry cabinet director kidnapped · Gran Grif Artibonite massacres · Chérizier reframing as anti-elite 'revolutionaries'<br/><b>Gov:</b> UN Security Council: Res 2699/GSF authorization; Viv Ansanm sanctions listing (2653 Committee, 8 Jul 2025); Chérizier + Izo listed | US State Dept / DNI-NCTC: FTO + Specially Designated Global Terrorist (May 2025); $5M bounty on Chérizier; NCTC group profile | UNODC / IOM: UNODC: crisis increasingly regional (arms/drug trafficking); IOM: 1.5M IDPs, 'even more alarming phase'<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Haiti enters at 94 — the Western Hemisphere's most acute security collapse. It is a criminal insurgency that has functionally displaced the state: no president, a transitional government winding down, security forces outgunned, and an underfunded, understrength international force as the only counterweight. The Pan-Africanist dimension is Viv Ansanm's ideological self-fashioning as defenders of the Black poor against 'oligarchs and colonial powers' — a narrative Crisis Group documents even as the gangs prey on the very communities they claim to represent.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-72.3,18.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇨🇺 Cuba — Post-Intervention Shock + Strangulation ◆</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Cuba — Post-Intervention Shock + Strangulation</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Caribbean | <b>Index:</b> 66/100 (Δ +3)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 32 Cuban soldiers killed in Jan 3 Caracas op; sanctions-linked excess-death risk (Lancet: 564k/yr globally from sanctions)<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW THEATER (backfilled) · JUL 6: total national grid collapse — 3rd this year, 7th in 18 months (Nuevitas Unit 6 cascade) · US cut Cuba's oil when it captured Maduro (Jan) + forced acting Venezuela govt to halt shipments; Mexico also halted a shipment under US tariff threat · only ONE oil tanker (Russian Anatoli Kolodkin, Matanzas) docked all year · May: Trump exec order sanctioning Cuba energy/defense/mining/finance sectors · US NOW SEEKS DÍAZ-CANEL OUSTER (NYT/AP) + regime change 'by end of year'; talks ongoing, Cuba released 2,000+ prisoners as goodwill · Trump: 'Cuba is next... I'll have the honor of taking Cuba' · Axios: US intel claims Cuba acquired 300+ Russia/Iran attack drones since 2023, 'discussed plans to attack US' — Cuba calls it fraudulent pretext for military action · Díaz-Canel: 'genocidal energy blockade,' calls for 'war of the entire nation' · UN: ~100,000 pending surgeries backlog, humanitarian 'collapse' risk; blackouts up to 15+ hrs/day · Bejucal SIGINT (China) cross-link retained<br/><b>Gov:</b> Cuban Government (official): Confirmed 32 soldiers killed 'carrying out missions' at Venezuela's request; Díaz-Canel condemned 'state terrorism' | US policy (Brookings/CRS synthesis): Oil-to-Cuba interdiction intended to immiserate and spur uprising against the 'Castroite regime' | US Executive Order (May 2026): Authorizes sanctioning entities in Cuba's energy, defense, mining, and financial sectors<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> United States (Energy interdiction) [HIGH] | Russia (Oil lifeline) [MED]<br/><b>◆ External actors:</b> 🇺🇸 US→pressure/regime-change [DOCUMENTED]: Oil blockade (cut Venezuela + pressured Mexico to halt shipments); May exec order sanctioning energy/defense/mining/finance; explicit push for Díaz-Canel ouster | 🇷🇺 Russia→regime lifeline [DOCUMENTED]: Anatoli Kolodkin tanker (Matanzas) — the ONLY oil shipment to dock all year; reaffirmed commitment; alleged attack-drone supplier (Axios) | 🇨🇳 China→regime [ALLEGED]: Bejucal SIGINT station (contested); economic-lifeline potential | 🇮🇷 Iran→regime [ALLEGED]: Alleged co-supplier of the 300+ attack drones (Axios/US intel) — same Mohajer/Shahed line as Venezuela/Sahel<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Cuba rises to 66, now escalating rather than stalemate. The July 6 island-wide grid collapse — the third total blackout of the year and seventh in 18 months — makes the strangulation strategy's endpoint concrete: with only one oil tanker (Russian) docked all year, the Soviet-era grid is failing outright. Washington has moved from pressure to explicit regime change, openly seeking Díaz-Canel's ouster and, per Trump, 'taking Cuba' next after Venezuela and Iran. The Axios drone-attack allegation — which Cuba calls a fraudulent pretext for military action — echoes the exact information-operation p<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-political</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-82.4,23.1,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇯🇲 Jamaica — Security Turnaround (Counter-Case)</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Jamaica — Security Turnaround (Counter-Case)</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Caribbean | <b>Index:</b> 42/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> DE-ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> ~673 murders 2025 (31-yr low, -43%); 33 in Jan 2026 (record-low month)<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW · COUNTER-CASE (de-escalating) · 31-year murder low: ~673 in 2025 (-43%), 33 in Jan 2026 = lowest month since records began 2001 · built on 20+ States of Emergency since 2018 · ACLED warns SoEs don't durably suppress gangs + carry police-brutality costs · still among highest per-capita murder rates in hemisphere<br/><b>Gov:</b> Jamaica OPM / JCF: PM Holness: 33 murders Jan 2026 = lowest month since 2001; Plan Secure Jamaica framework | STATIN / JIS: ~673 murders 2025 = 31-year low, -43%; -32% shootings; official national statistics | US State Dept OSAC: JCF reported 666 murders Jan-Dec 27 2025 (-41.7%); still among highest per-capita in hemisphere<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Jamaica enters at 42, trend down — the platform's clearest de-escalation and a methodological anchor: it proves the framework tracks improvement, not just crisis. The turnaround is real and government-data-verified, but fragile — built on emergency powers ACLED judges non-durable, and still leaving Jamaica among the hemisphere's highest per-capita murder rates. The counter-case to Haiti's collapse next door.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-77.3,18.1,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
