<Placemark><name>🇺🇸 US Foreign Policy — Strikes + Brokerage</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>US Foreign Policy — Strikes + Brokerage</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> North America | <b>Index:</b> 64/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> VOLATILE<br/><b>Human cost:</b> N/A<br/><b>Note:</b> Struck Iran (10 targets) + brokered Lebanon + Doha Jun 30 · UAE arms-sale fork on Sudan · African visa-embassy drawdown · DONROE DOCTRINE: post-Maduro corollary asserting right to intervene at will in Western Hemisphere — Venezuela occupied-by-leverage, Mexico indictments, Colombia election endorsement, Cuba strangulation · Congress notified of "non-international armed conflict" with cartels<br/><b>Gov:</b> US State Dept: 3 mediation tracks (Doha, Lebanon, Sudan-Boulos); African visa-processing drawdown | US CENTCOM: 10-target Iran strike<br/><b>Assessment:</b> US foreign policy holds at 63 — striking Iran while running three mediation tracks. The central tension: US leverage over the UAE is the most effective unused lever on Sudan, yet the UAE is needed for the Iran coalition. Volatile stays right.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-political</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-77,38.9,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇲🇽 Mexico — Cartel-FTO Confrontation / Sovereignty Squeeze</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Mexico — Cartel-FTO Confrontation / Sovereignty Squeeze</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> North America | <b>Index:</b> 62/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Cartel violence ongoing; no US kinetic strikes on Mexican soil to date<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW THEATER (backfilled from W1) · APR 29 (=our W1): DOJ indicted 10 Mexican officials incl. SITTING Sinaloa Gov. Rubén Rocha Moya (AMLO ally, Morena), Sen. Inzunza, Culiacán mayor — extradition demanded · Nat'l Drug Control Strategy 2026: cartels = FTOs, fentanyl = WMD, extraterritorial-ops authority · Trump post-Maduro: 'We are going to start hitting land... The cartels are running Mexico' · Sheinbaum: charges 'political'; first public criticism of Amb. Johnson in 14 months; ~70% approval · cooperation continues: 10,000 troops to border, 90+ extraditions · Jun: Sheinbaum rejects Espriella labeling Mexican cartels military targets; warns vs Mexico as Nov-2026-midterm rhetoric · UPDATE (Jul): Sheinbaum publicly rebuffed Colombia President-elect Espriella's designation of Mexican cartels as military targets in Colombian territory ('each sovereign nation manages its own internal security'); warned again against Mexico as US Nov-2026-midterm rhetoric · skipped Trump's 'Shield of the Americas' Doral summit (with Lula + Petro) — the 3 big left-led economies absent · Americas Counter-Cartel Coalition (A3C, Hegseth/SOUTHCOM Miami) advancing around her · still NO US strikes on Mexican soil; Rocha Moya extradition decision still pending<br/><b>Gov:</b> US DOJ / DEA (Cole): Apr 29: 10 officials charged incl. sitting Sinaloa governor — 'No one is above the law'; extradition requested | National Drug Control Strategy 2026: Cartels designated FTOs; fentanyl classified WMD; measurable compliance benchmarks; expanded extraterritorial authority | Sheinbaum govt: Rejected charges as political; 10,000 security forces deployed to border; 90+ extraditions delivered; record-low migration flows<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Mexico enters at 62, trend up. This is the hemisphere's most consequential slow-burn: the Venezuela precedent plus the FTO/WMD legal stack means the distance from indictments to kinetic action is shorter than it has ever been, while mutual dependence (migration for Trump, exports for Mexico) is the stabilizer neither side can afford to break. The Rocha Moya extradition decision is the fuse to watch — it forces Sheinbaum to choose between her party and her northern flank. JULY UPDATE: Sheinbaum is holding the line — no US strikes have hit Mexican soil, she skipped Trump's Doral 'Shield of the A<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-political</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>-99.13,19.43,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Middle East</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🌐 US–Israel vs. Iran — Spike &amp; Settle</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>US–Israel vs. Iran — Spike &amp; Settle</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Middle East | <b>Index:</b> 78/100 (Δ -1)<br/><b>Status:</b> VOLATILE<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Khamenei killed in opening salvo; Gulf capitals struck<br/><b>Note:</b> Doha indirect talks made "positive progress" (Qatar); Iran left for Khamenei multi-day funeral (Jul 4-9); next round "earliest possible" after · Araghchi in Iraq: "Strait of Hormuz remains under total oversight and management of Iran throughout the coming 30 days" · MOU deadline now AUG 17 (17 days in, 43 remaining) · Kushner+Witkoff pressing Iran to drop toll plan; Rubio: any toll "makes a deal unfeasible" · transit ~25 vessels/day vs 110 pre-war; UAE oil co: full Hormuz flows won't resume until 2027 · new Supreme Leader Mojtaba Khamenei has "different view" than Pezeshkian on MOU<br/><b>Gov:</b> US CENTCOM: Confirmed 10-target strike; 'powerful response' | Bahrain/Kuwait govts: Condemned Iranian strikes as 'dangerous escalation' | Iran parliament (Azizi): Strait 'governed by Iran'; strike was 'ceasefire management' | Iran state TV (Qalibaf): 'Sovereignty of the Strait of Hormuz lies with Iran and Oman' — joint-administration + passage-fee claim after 60-day MOU | Qatar MOFA: 'Positive progress' on Islamabad MOU issues; next meeting after Khamenei funeral ends July 9; emergency communication channel agreed<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> Qatar / US (Frozen assets + reconstruction) [HIGH]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Iran-US holds at 78, volatile. The July 4 truce cliff passed quietly on the US Independence Day pause rather than in renewed clashes — a de-escalation by calendar accident more than design. Talks made 'positive progress' in Doha before Iran broke for Khamenei's multi-day funeral (July 4-9), with the next round to follow. But the structure hardened: Araghchi extended the sovereignty doctrine ('total oversight and management of Iran throughout the coming 30 days'), the MOU clock now runs to August 17, and the new Supreme Leader Mojtaba Khamenei reportedly holds a 'different view' than the electe<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>51,32,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇵🇸 Israel–Gaza War</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Israel–Gaza War</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Middle East | <b>Index:</b> 77/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> STALEMATE<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 73,074+ Palestinians killed (20,179 children); 1,072+ killed since ceasefire began<br/><b>Note:</b> Shaky ceasefire (since Oct 10 2025) persists · JUL 6: HAMAS DISSOLVED its Gaza government to hand to Palestinian technocratic committee (NCAG) — symbolic pressure on Israel; made NO mention of disarmament · phase TWO launched (last hostage body returned; Board of Peace 'productive' Cyprus meetings) but NCAG stuck in Cairo, int'l stabilization force hasn't materialized · Israel seizing ~70% of Strip (Netanyahu May 28 order), won't withdraw past 'yellow line' · toll: 73,074+ killed (20,179 children) since Oct 2023; 1,072+ killed in 3,463 wounded since ceasefire (≈1 child/day) · Jun: UN commission found ongoing genocide (Israel: 'political blood libel') · reconstruction est. $70B<br/><b>Gov:</b> UNRWA: 73,000+ Palestinian deaths (mid-2026) | Board of Peace (Mladenov): Gaza demilitarization plan apparently rejected by Hamas<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Gaza holds at 77. The July 6 move is significant diplomatically if not on the ground: Hamas dissolved its government to hand governance to the technocratic NCAG — but pointedly omitted disarmament, the phase-two crux — putting symbolic pressure back on Israel while changing nothing about who controls the streets. Phase two has 'launched' (last hostage body returned, Board of Peace meeting in Cyprus), yet the NCAG remains stuck in Cairo, the international stabilization force hasn't materialized, Israel is seizing ~70% of the Strip, and the toll keeps climbing (73,074+; roughly one child a day s<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>34.3,31.35,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🇱🇧 Lebanon — Framework Signed (Contested)</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Lebanon — Framework Signed (Contested)</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Middle East | <b>Index:</b> 75/100 (Δ -1)<br/><b>Status:</b> VOLATILE<br/><b>Human cost:</b> IDF Cpt. Hazutt killed; hundreds since Apr 17<br/><b>Note:</b> Trilateral framework SIGNED Jun 26 — IDF withdraws from 2 pilot zones, LAF oversees disarmament · Hezbollah (Qassem): 'null &amp; void' · Katz: not 'a millimeter' more · Haaretz: 'Gaza Strip 2' · permanent-deal odds 1.4% · Israeli drone strikes/artillery continued across the south (Nabatieh al-Fawqa, Bint Jbeil) despite framework; relief volunteers under fire · US told Iran at Doha it would "restrain Israel"; pilot-zone withdrawal framed as "first step" · Israeli strikes continued across south post-framework; permanent-deal odds remain low; US "restrain Israel" pledge untested<br/><b>Gov:</b> US State Dept (Rubio): Announced framework as 'beginning of the beginning' | Israel (Katz): 'No territorial ambitions' but won't withdraw 'a millimeter' beyond pilot zones | Lebanese government: Signed; declared Hezbollah 'enemy of Lebanon'<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Lebanon holds at 76 — it rose because the framework got signed, but of its three negotiation strands one is signed, one collapsed (disarmament), and one stalled. The signed paper may institutionalize an indefinite Israeli presence rather than resolve anything.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>35.4,33.3,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Europe</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇺🇦 Russia–Ukraine War</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Russia–Ukraine War</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Europe | <b>Index:</b> 85/100 (Δ +1)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> ~1.4M Russian casualties (Ukraine est.); 250-300k Ukrainian<br/><b>Note:</b> REVERSAL of the Dec25-May26 net-loss picture: DeepState OSINT — Russia made a NET GAIN of ~31 sq mi (June 2-30 2026), grinding at Pokrovsk (mostly Russian-controlled by Jan 2026), Siversk, Huliaipole, Kupiansk; took parts of Dnipropetrovsk + Sumy · BUT CSIS: still &lt;1.5% of Ukraine taken since 2024, Pokrovsk pace ~70m/day (slower than the Somme); Russia ~1.2M casualties / up to 325k killed · Ukraine lost Kursk foothold in spring; on the defensive · Russian economy strained (deficit, expensive ruble, low oil) but hasn't buckled · Jul 7: active clashes Pokrovsk/Lyman/Kupiansk directions<br/><b>Gov:</b> ISW / Critical Threats Project: Russia gained 40.64 sq km but lost 281.1 sq km Dec25-May26; 7.87% of 2025 pace | Ukraine General Staff: Record ~660-drone assault; Pokrovsk-direction advances<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Ukraine rises to 85. This reverses the v14 read: after the winter's net-loss period, Russia is again making incremental net gains (~31 sq mi in June per DeepState), has taken most of Pokrovsk, and pushed into Dnipropetrovsk and Sumy. The crucial caveat holds — CSIS notes Russia has still seized under 1.5% of Ukrainian territory since 2024, advancing at a Somme-slow ~70m/day for approximately 1.2M casualties. It is grinding progress, not breakthrough, bought at historically extreme cost, with the Russian economy strained but unbroken. Ukraine is back on the defensive across the eastern front.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>32,49,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>South Asia</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇵🇰 Pakistan–Afghanistan War</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Pakistan–Afghanistan War</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> South Asia | <b>Index:</b> 74/100 (Δ -2)<br/><b>Status:</b> STALEMATE<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 289+ civilian casualties; Mandokhail strike killed children<br/><b>Note:</b> Gulf-powers + Türkiye brokering has calmed the Afghanistan-Pakistan dispute (Crisis Group: Xi left it to them while propping up Myanmar junta) · low-intensity Durand Line exchanges continue but no major flare-up since the Mandokhail strikes · both nuclear-armed; TTP safe-haven problem unresolved · Pakistan retains Iran-deal mediator standing (co-brokered Doha w/ Qatar; PM Sharif attending Khamenei funeral)<br/><b>Gov:</b> Taliban officials: Report Pakistani airstrikes killed civilians incl. children at Mandokhail | Pakistan (via RFERL): Co-mediating US-Iran Doha track with Qatar<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Pakistan-Afghanistan eases to 74. The border dispute has settled into a managed, lower-intensity state under Gulf and Turkish brokering, with no major flare-up since the Mandokhail strikes. Crisis Group frames it as a conflict others are containing while Washington is absent. Pakistan's diplomatic stock stays elevated via its Iran-deal mediation role (PM Sharif is at Khamenei's funeral), but the structural problems — the TTP safe haven, nuclear adjacency — remain unresolved.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>69.2,33.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>East Asia</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇹🇼 Taiwan Strait — China Gray Zone</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Taiwan Strait — China Gray Zone</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> East Asia | <b>Index:</b> 70/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> No kinetic casualties<br/><b>Note:</b> Crisis Group: Trump 'has not revised US policy on Taiwan' — hard to imagine ceding the high-end chip industry or regional primacy to China · PLA gray-zone pressure continues; no kinetic change · China remains largest Hormuz oil customer (stake in Iran ceasefire holding) · G7 Critical Minerals Alliance still targeting China rare-earth/magnet dominance; TSMC 90%+ advanced chips = the mutual hold<br/><b>Gov:</b> G7 / Élysée: Critical Minerals Alliance vs China rare-earth dependence<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> Mutual (PRC/Taiwan) (Semiconductors vs rare earths) [HIGH]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Taiwan holds at 70. Crisis Group confirms US policy is explicitly unchanged — Washington has not revised its Taiwan stance and is not about to cede the semiconductor industry or regional primacy to Beijing. The gray-zone pressure and the mutual supply-chain hold (TSMC chips vs. Chinese rare earths) are steady. China's large stake in the Iran ceasefire holding is the indirect linkage that keeps Taiwan coupled to the Middle East theaters.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>121,23.7,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Global</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🔭 Maritime Chokepoints — Hormuz Managed-Access</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Maritime Chokepoints — Hormuz Managed-Access</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Global | <b>Index:</b> 66/100 (Δ -1)<br/><b>Status:</b> VOLATILE<br/><b>Human cost:</b> N/A<br/><b>Note:</b> Hormuz "managed recovery" but transit only ~25 vessels/day vs 110 pre-war; WTO: 95% drop crude / 99% drop LNG; UAE oil co says full flows not until 2027 · Iran designated-route warnings continue (vessels using Omani coast to evade); "immediate and firm response" threatened · Houthis resumed Red Sea (2 ships sunk); Bab el-Mandeb second stressed chokepoint · war-risk insurance elevated, carriers still on Cape of Good Hope routing<br/><b>Gov:</b> Iran FM Araghchi: Warns against 'separate arrangements'; claims sole Hormuz control | US/GCC/Oman: Reject any Iranian toll/control claim<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Chokepoints ease to 65 as the stand-down restored transit, but the structure hardened: Iran demonstrated and doctrinally asserted managed access. Doha Jun 30 takes up Hormuz management — the most consequential maritime negotiation on the board.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-strategic</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>50,25,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>🔭 Geopolitical Blocs — AES / Gulf / China-Cuba</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Geopolitical Blocs — AES / Gulf / China-Cuba</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Global | <b>Index:</b> 60/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> WATCH<br/><b>Human cost:</b> N/A — analytical + intelligence layer<br/><b>Note:</b> UPDATED · AES Confederation as sovereignty bloc: 15,000 Unified Force, joint passport/bank, 0.5% import levy, quit ECOWAS, reciprocal US travel-ban response · Gulf = $6B custodian + Doha venue + $300B · Bejucal SIGINT · OTS-Hungary · AES condemnation of US over Venezuela/Maduro now has full context: the Jan 3 capture + Donroe Doctrine — Pan-African + Latin American sovereignty pushback converging · EXTERNAL-ACTOR LAYER (v16): three patronage models mapped into W/C Africa — gold-for-guns (Russia/UAE), drone diplomacy (Turkey/China), aid-as-cover/aid-washing (UAE, Qatar softer). US aid withdrawal (~83% Sub-Saharan cut) + French expulsion created the vacuum. Qatar Al Mansour $103bn pledge + UAE now a top-3 Africa investor; Iran-war may delay $100B+ Gulf African investment.<br/><b>Gov:</b> AES communiqués: Unified Force launch (Dec 2025); import levy; reciprocal US travel ban; condemned US over Venezuela/Maduro | ISS Africa / Amani Africa: AES financing via national funds; central question is funding the force without donors | AU Peace &amp; Security Council: June 2026 review; late-response critique; AES-ECOWAS Abuja engagement<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> AES bloc (Sovereign funds + levy) [MED]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> The strategic layer rises to 60 with the AES added as a formal sovereignty bloc — the political-strategic counterpart to the Sahel-core military theaters. Its resource-sovereignty doctrine and anti-French realignment are consolidating institutionally even as the security justification for the coups goes unmet. The Gulf remains the decisive swing hinge of the Iran settlement.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-strategic</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>0.0,10.0,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>📊 Global Economy — Contained Through Exchange</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Global Economy — Contained Through Exchange</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Global | <b>Index:</b> 55/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Status:</b> DE-ESCALATING<br/><b>Human cost:</b> War cost: airlines $6.5B/mo fuel at peak<br/><b>Note:</b> Oil 'relatively contained' through exchange (Swissquote) — reserve releases + oversupply · $6B Iran assets unfrozen · Kenya/Comoros fuel protests · shipping normalization slowed not reversed<br/><b>Gov:</b> IMF: Pre-war growth track (3.3%) holding through the stress test | Qatar: Released $6B in frozen Iranian assets<br/><b>Assessment:</b> The global economy ticks to 55, improving — the recovery proved resilient to exactly the Hormuz flare-up that would have spiked prices three months ago. Iran's Hormuz control remains a 'hi' lever, but its macro bite is being absorbed.<br/><i>v17.0 · Week 13 verify</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-economic</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
